#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:4
msgid "How to manage logging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:6
msgid ""
"pytest captures log messages of level ``WARNING`` or above automatically and "
"displays them in their own section for each failed test in the same manner "
"as captured stdout and stderr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:9
msgid "Running without options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:11
msgid "pytest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:15 ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:38
msgid "Shows failed tests like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:17
msgid ""
"----------------------- Captured stdlog call ----------------------\n"
"test_reporting.py    26 WARNING  text going to logger\n"
"----------------------- Captured stdout call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stdout\n"
"----------------------- Captured stderr call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stderr\n"
"==================== 2 failed in 0.02 seconds ====================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:27
msgid ""
"By default each captured log message shows the module, line number, log "
"level and message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:30
msgid ""
"If desired the log and date format can be specified to anything that the "
"logging module supports by passing specific formatting options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:33
msgid ""
"pytest --log-format=\"%(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s\" \\\n"
"        --log-date-format=\"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:40
msgid ""
"----------------------- Captured stdlog call ----------------------\n"
"2010-04-10 14:48:44 WARNING text going to logger\n"
"----------------------- Captured stdout call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stdout\n"
"----------------------- Captured stderr call ----------------------\n"
"text going to stderr\n"
"==================== 2 failed in 0.02 seconds ====================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:50
msgid "These options can also be customized through a configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:54
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_format = \"%(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s\"\n"
"log_date_format = \"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:62
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_format = %(asctime)s %(levelname)s %(message)s\n"
"log_date_format = %Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:68
msgid ""
"Specific loggers can be disabled via :option:`--log-disable={logger_name}`. "
"This argument can be passed multiple times:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:71
msgid "pytest --log-disable=main --log-disable=testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:75
msgid ""
"Further it is possible to disable reporting of captured content (stdout, "
"stderr and logs) on failed tests completely with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:78
msgid "pytest --show-capture=no"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:84
msgid "caplog fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:86
msgid ""
"Inside tests it is possible to change the log level for the captured log "
"messages.  This is supported by the ``caplog`` fixture:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:89
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    caplog.set_level(logging.INFO)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:94
msgid ""
"By default the level is set on the root logger, however as a convenience it "
"is also possible to set the log level of any logger:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:98
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    caplog.set_level(logging.CRITICAL, logger=\"root.baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:103
msgid "The log levels set are restored automatically at the end of the test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:105
msgid ""
"It is also possible to use a context manager to temporarily change the log "
"level inside a ``with`` block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:108
msgid ""
"def test_bar(caplog):\n"
"    with caplog.at_level(logging.INFO):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:114
msgid ""
"Again, by default the level of the root logger is affected but the level of "
"any logger can be changed instead with:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:117
msgid ""
"def test_bar(caplog):\n"
"    with caplog.at_level(logging.CRITICAL, logger=\"root.baz\"):\n"
"        pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:123
msgid ""
"Lastly all the logs sent to the logger during the test run are made "
"available on the fixture in the form of both the ``logging.LogRecord`` "
"instances and the final log text. This is useful for when you want to assert "
"on the contents of a message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:127
msgid ""
"def test_baz(caplog):\n"
"    func_under_test()\n"
"    for record in caplog.records:\n"
"        assert record.levelname != \"CRITICAL\"\n"
"    assert \"wally\" not in caplog.text"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:135
msgid ""
"For all the available attributes of the log records see the ``logging."
"LogRecord`` class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:138
msgid ""
"You can also resort to ``record_tuples`` if all you want to do is to ensure, "
"that certain messages have been logged under a given logger name with a "
"given severity and message:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:142
msgid ""
"def test_foo(caplog):\n"
"    logging.getLogger().info(\"boo %s\", \"arg\")\n"
"\n"
"    assert caplog.record_tuples == [(\"root\", logging.INFO, \"boo arg\")]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:149
msgid ""
"You can call ``caplog.clear()`` to reset the captured log records in a test:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:151
msgid ""
"def test_something_with_clearing_records(caplog):\n"
"    some_method_that_creates_log_records()\n"
"    caplog.clear()\n"
"    your_test_method()\n"
"    assert [\"Foo\"] == [rec.message for rec in caplog.records]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:160
msgid ""
"The ``caplog.records`` attribute contains records from the current stage "
"only, so inside the ``setup`` phase it contains only setup logs, same with "
"the ``call`` and ``teardown`` phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:164
msgid ""
"To access logs from other stages, use the ``caplog.get_records(when)`` "
"method. As an example, if you want to make sure that tests which use a "
"certain fixture never log any warnings, you can inspect the records for the "
"``setup`` and ``call`` stages during teardown like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:168
msgid ""
"@pytest.fixture\n"
"def window(caplog):\n"
"    window = create_window()\n"
"    yield window\n"
"    for when in (\"setup\", \"call\"):\n"
"        messages = [\n"
"            x.message for x in caplog.get_records(when) if x.levelno == "
"logging.WARNING\n"
"        ]\n"
"        if messages:\n"
"            pytest.fail(f\"warning messages encountered during testing: "
"{messages}\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:183
msgid "The full API is available at :class:`pytest.LogCaptureFixture`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:187
msgid ""
"The ``caplog`` fixture adds a handler to the root logger to capture logs. If "
"the root logger is modified during a test, for example with ``logging.config."
"dictConfig``, this handler may be removed and cause no logs to be captured. "
"To avoid this, ensure that any root logger configuration only adds to the "
"existing handlers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:196
msgid "Live Logs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:198
msgid ""
"By setting the :confval:`log_cli` configuration option to ``true``, pytest "
"will output logging records as they are emitted directly into the console."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:201
msgid ""
"You can specify the logging level for which log records with equal or higher "
"level are printed to the console by passing :option:`--log-cli-level`. This "
"setting accepts the logging level names or numeric values as seen in :ref:"
"`logging's documentation <python:levels>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:206
msgid ""
"Additionally, you can also specify :option:`--log-cli-format` and :option:`--"
"log-cli-date-format` which mirror and default to :option:`--log-format` and :"
"option:`--log-date-format` if not provided, but are applied only to the "
"console logging handler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:211
msgid ""
"All of the CLI log options can also be set in the configuration file. The "
"option names are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:214
msgid ":confval:`log_cli_level`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:215
msgid ":confval:`log_cli_format`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:216
msgid ":confval:`log_cli_date_format`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:218
msgid ""
"If you need to record the whole test suite logging calls to a file, you can "
"pass :option:`--log-file=/path/to/log/file`. This log file is opened in "
"write mode by default, which means that it will be overwritten at each test "
"session. If you'd like the file opened in append mode instead, then you can "
"pass :option:`--log-file-mode=a`. Note that relative paths for the log-file "
"location, whether passed on the CLI or declared in a config file, are always "
"resolved relative to the current working directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:225
msgid ""
"You can also specify the logging level for the log file by passing :option:"
"`--log-file-level`. This setting accepts the logging level names or numeric "
"values as seen in :ref:`logging's documentation <python:levels>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:229
msgid ""
"Additionally, you can also specify :option:`--log-file-format` and :option:"
"`--log-file-date-format` which are equal to ``--log-format`` and :option:`--"
"log-date-format` but are applied to the log file logging handler."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:233
msgid ""
"All of the log file options can also be set in the configuration file. The "
"option names are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:236
msgid ":confval:`log_file`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:237
msgid ":confval:`log_file_mode`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:238
msgid ":confval:`log_file_level`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:239
msgid ":confval:`log_file_format`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:240
msgid ":confval:`log_file_date_format`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:242
msgid ""
"You can call ``set_log_path()`` to customize the log_file path dynamically. "
"This functionality is considered **experimental**. Note that "
"``set_log_path()`` respects the :confval:`log_file_mode` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:248
msgid "Customizing Colors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:250
msgid ""
"Log levels are colored if colored terminal output is enabled. Changing from "
"default colors or putting color on custom log levels is supported through "
"``add_color_level()``. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:254
msgid ""
"@pytest.hookimpl(trylast=True)\n"
"def pytest_configure(config):\n"
"    logging_plugin = config.pluginmanager.get_plugin(\"logging-plugin\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Change color on existing log level\n"
"    logging_plugin.log_cli_handler.formatter.add_color_level(logging.INFO, "
"\"cyan\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Add color to a custom log level (a custom log level `SPAM` is already "
"set up)\n"
"    logging_plugin.log_cli_handler.formatter.add_color_level(logging.SPAM, "
"\"blue\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:267
msgid ""
"This feature and its API are considered **experimental** and might change "
"between releases without a deprecation notice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:272
msgid "Release notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:274
msgid ""
"This feature was introduced as a drop-in replacement for the :pypi:`pytest-"
"catchlog` plugin and they conflict with each other. The backward "
"compatibility API with ``pytest-capturelog`` has been dropped when this "
"feature was introduced, so if for that reason you still need ``pytest-"
"catchlog`` you can disable the internal feature by adding to your "
"configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:283
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = [\"-p\", \"no:logging\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:290
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = -p no:logging"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:299
msgid "Incompatible changes in pytest 3.4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:301
msgid ""
"This feature was introduced in ``3.3`` and some **incompatible changes** "
"have been made in ``3.4`` after community feedback:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:304
msgid ""
"Log levels are no longer changed unless explicitly requested by the :confval:"
"`log_level` configuration or :option:`--log-level` command-line options. "
"This allows users to configure logger objects themselves. Setting :confval:"
"`log_level` will set the level that is captured globally so if a specific "
"test requires a lower level than this, use the ``caplog.set_level()`` "
"functionality otherwise that test will be prone to failure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:309
msgid ""
":ref:`Live Logs <live_logs>` is now disabled by default and can be enabled "
"setting the :confval:`log_cli` configuration option to ``true``. When "
"enabled, the verbosity is increased so logging for each test is visible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:312
msgid ""
":ref:`Live Logs <live_logs>` are now sent to ``sys.stdout`` and no longer "
"require the :option:`-s` command-line option to work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:315
msgid ""
"If you want to partially restore the logging behavior of version ``3.3``, "
"you can add these options to your configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:320
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_cli = true\n"
"log_level = \"NOTSET\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:328
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"log_cli = true\n"
"log_level = NOTSET"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/how-to/logging.rst:334
msgid ""
"More details about the discussion that led to these changes can be read in :"
"issue:`3013`."
msgstr ""
